Children of Heracles, Hecuba, Medea, Electra, and Orestes.Burnett shows that for the ancients, revenge meant a redress of imbalances in both human and divine worlds, achieved through human actions. The vengeful heroines thus appear in a new light. Electra, Hecuba, Medea, and others cease to be the picture of depravity in dramas that are grotesque and sensational, and are instead representative human figures who respond with grandeur to the outsize demands of necessity and supernatural powers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aRevenge in literature. 4aAeschylus. 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aEuripides. 4aEuropean literature. 4aMedea. 4aOdyssey. 4aOthers. 4aOvid. 4aPlato. 4aSophocles. 4aancient Greek history. 4aancient philosophy. 4aclassical antiquity. 4aclassical literature. 4aethics. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of philosophy. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory of western philosophy. 4ahistory. 4aliterature. 4amoral philosophy. 4amoral. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 4atime. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919952?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919952/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles